  |     |
  | --- |
  | Hello,<br>My goal here is to have two different application/json+ld scripts in the head when I'm on a product page. 1 organizational that sits on all pages and 1 for individual product pages. I've simplified things just for the sake of the discussion. [Here](https://codesandbox.io/p/sandbox/goofy-julien-vqffs6?selection=%5B%7B%22endColumn%22%3A1%2C%22endLineNumber%22%3A24%2C%22startColumn%22%3A1%2C%22startLineNumber%22%3A24%7D%5D&file=%2Fpackage.json) is a code sandbox that lays out a couple different strategies I've tried that have not worked.<br>1. Components representing the script tag inserted between head on \_document and the product page. (GlobalSEO and ProductSEO)<br>2. Components wrapped in Head placed in \_document and product outside the head. (WrappedGlobalSEO and WrappedProductSEO).<br>3. bare script tags in the head of \_document and product<br>Interestingly, it appears the only way to get product page to have the product schema is to actually remove the global schema json altogether.<br>Another tactic might be to create some kind of super component that produces a json+ld array, 0th position having the organizational data and then conditionally adding another index for the product data if those props exist, but that would be a fair amount of code repetition. Is there a better way?<br>Some threads I've been looking over that may or may not be related: [#22729](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/22729), [#11012](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/11012), and [#9126](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/9126). This [comment](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/22729#issuecomment-974516530), in particular, seemed to suggest it was completely possible, but I haven't had luck using that method (third on the list above). |
  
  BetaWas this translation helpful? [Give feedback.](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/discussions/44836#)
  
