  | You could define a data getter at page level, and then from within \_app collect the page data, if any, and merge that with some baseline/defaults.<br>```<br>import type { AppProps } from "next/app";<br>type AnyObject = Record<string, unknown>;<br>type Data = {'@content': string; '@type': string; name: string; pid: number}<br>export type MyPage<P = AnyObject, IP = AnyObject> = NextPage<P, IP> & {<br>    getJSONStructuredData?: (pageProps: P) => Array<Data>;<br>};<br>type MyAppProps = AppProps & {<br>    Component: MyPage;<br>}<br>const MyApp = ({Component, pageProps, initialState}: MyAppProps) =>  {<br>    return (<br>        <>   <br>                <InjectSEO pageOwnData={Component?.getJSONStructuredData?.(pageProps)} /><br>                <Component {...pageProps} /><br>        </><br>    );<br>}<br>```<br>And then each page can opt-in to implementing `getJSONStructruredData`:<br>```<br>const Product: MyPage<ProductProps> = () => <div>P</div><br>// props here is typed as ProductProps<br>Product. getJSONStructuredData = (props) => { return [ /* something */] } <br>```<br>Pretty much the way shared layouts work in Next.js pages directory: [https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/layouts](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/layouts)<br>The InjectSEO component takes care of filling in defaults ~ |
  
